content:
Dashboards help you visually understand changing business conditions so you can make decisions based on the real-time data you’ve gathered with reports.

Reports provide all the data shown in a dashboard. Dashboards can show data from more than one report.

When refreshing a dashboard, all the data-providing reports must run. If the reports take a long time to run, then the dashboard does too.

Dashboards are shared via folders. Whomever has permission to the folder your dashboard is saved in also has access to your dashboard.

The Dashboard Editor is a visual, drag-and-drop tool, which you use to create dashboards and edit existing ones.

Widgets are the building blocks of dashboards. Each widget contains a chart or metric that shows data from one report.

A dashboard only displays data that the dashboard’s running user can access.

Build a dashboard by curating data from reports using charts, tables, and metrics.

Dashboard filters make it easy for users to apply different data perspectives to a single dashboard.

You can control which data is visible based on the running user.

Subscribe to or schedule dashboards to receive refreshed results by email on a schedule that you set.

A sales overview dashboard is a great way for teams to collaborate on opportunities because it provides a complete picture of your pipeline.

To improve dashboard performance, optimize source reports and plan dashboard refreshes.

If a dashboard is running slowly, check if the source reports are inefficient or many people are refreshing it at once.
title: Understanding Salesforce Dashboards
